      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Because s-reduction is a gradient feature, analysts often use acoustic measures to determine the extent of reduction and to classify tokens allophonically. This typically involves at least a combined Center of Gravity (COG) and Standard Deviation (SD) Measurement in Hertz (Hz). The COG measurement indicates the average frequency of the sound, whereas the SD indicates dispersion of sound relative to that average. That is, a high COG (~6-10kHz) and a low SD are indicative of a high frequency flow of concentrated air moving through a relatively small airway, which occurs with [s]. Contrastively, a lower COG and a higher SD indicate less-concentrated air moving through a larger opening, which occurs with [h]. These differences can also be confirmed visually using a spectrogram, as [s] presents as a high-frequency dark cluster. Below are spectrograms that showcase this variability, including two forms of deletion: one where the etymological place of /s/ is trace-marked with a pause, and another where the segment is elided entirely. "
        }
      ]
    },
