      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The alternation between these forms is not random, but conditioned by a combination of language-internal and -external factors, including phonological environment, interactional setting, role alignment, and encoded stance and affect. In Puerto Rico, sibilance [s] is contrasted against both [h] and [∅] along axes of differentation relating to notions of formality, education, and institutional authority. Aspiration is then further distinguished from deletion and sibilance along an axis of locality, being positively evaluated as an authentic marker of Puerto Rican identity. Of these variants, deletion is often reported as the most heavily stigmatized, though such evaluations are shown to be influenced in part by the stance and background of the hearer and their perceptions of the speaker's background. Moreover, some research suggests [s] carries gendered and sexuality-based associations, being heard as a \"feminine\" feature characteristic of the speech of women and gay men. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
