    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "center",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-two",
          "text": "/s/ in Reggaetón "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "center",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-two",
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "In musical performance, these variants are not only inherited from the spoken registers of the performers but strategically deployed as part of the stylization of the musical product. S-Reduction in reggaetón, in particular, plays a central role in constructing the voice of the genre, and is adopted by both speakers from within and without Puerto Rico. Its salience is so high that the feature is even visibly marked in online lyric transcriptions through the use of apostrophes (e.g., \""
        },
        {
          "text": "no me mire' así",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "\"). The following examples showcase how findings from contemporary research frame lenited /s/ as an enregistered resource for constructing and performing artistic alignment with the broader reggaetón soundscape. Throughout these examples, AVAnnotate's annotation feature provides transcriptions of the lyrics to highlight cases of reduction. For accessibility, this variability is presented binarily as \"retention [s] or reduction [h ʔ ø]\" marked in brackets as [s] or [-]. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "S-Reduction is consistently present in reggaetón throughout the genre's history, withstanding globalization and artistic innovation over the years. Listen below to hear how coda /s/ is highly absent in each of the songs, save for some prevocalic tokens. Reductions appear to be the norm in each song, whose release dates range from 1996 to 2022, to showcase the Underground, Luny Tunes, Latin-Pop, and Contemporary eras of reggaetón production. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
