      ],
      "event1": {
        "uuid": "d5375636-58c0-4e58-86c4-c9b76b44db8a",
        "start": 73,
        "end": 108,
        "file": "195f118b-1a96-43be-b76a-170554ea0d29",
        "type": "Video"
      },
      "event2": {
        "uuid": "4d25b3dd-e068-41bc-aa88-a479136dc4a6",
        "start": 189,
        "end": 235,
        "file": "5171571c-fbce-4be5-a4c2-633441b74a68",
        "type": "Video"
      },
      "type": "event-comparison",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The enregistered vernacularity of /s/ reduction and its general restriction to reggaetón/urbano music facilitate its use as a way of embodying the reggaetón voice, even if the singer themselves does not reduce /s/ to the same extent outside of reggaetón production. For this reason, use of reduced /s/ by artists of stereotypically s-retaining backgrounds in reggaetón has been a site of particular investigative interest. From this literature, a general tendency emerges. Singers, regardless of sociolinguistic and cultural background, tend to use significantly more reduced variants when performing reggaetón and reggaetón-derived tracks than in other genres of music and speech modalities. Listen below to hear this style shift in Catalonian singer Rosalía and Mexican-American singer Becky G's /s/ production: "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
