        "uuid": "4740008a-df36-48a7-925e-1557dbbe5020",
        "start": 240,
        "end": 287,
        "file": "6176e78c-a398-45eb-b1c4-8906c8ee866d",
        "type": "Video"
      },
      "event2": {
        "uuid": "769a5931-a631-4eca-a656-7ddefbc02aa5",
        "start": 105,
        "end": 164,
        "file": "11c52f6b-eb3d-4714-8944-1fe3fad3de38",
        "type": "Video"
      },
      "type": "event-comparison",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This tendency to use more reduction, but restricted to reggaetón, has also been documented in the music of both native and non-native speakers of Spanish, such as Medellinense singers J Balvin and Karol G and the Brazilian crossover artist Anitta. Moreover, the current research on /s/ production suggests that not only is reduction the preferred variant independent of artists' unique sociolinguistic backgrounds, but also that the rate of reduction across performances converges towards a range upwards of 50%. This is highly suggestive that reduced /s/ is now enregistered as a standard phonological element of the reggaetón voice. Importantly, this has been identified as a relatively novel and emergent pattern, first gaining widespread recognizability and conformity in the late 2010s and 2020s. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
